  "read": "Plan caching mechanically works and removes the repeated synchronized plan stage on cache hits, but a forever-cached hot-expert set becomes stale for learned routing: step-2 last-half remote rows collapse to median 0, so helper grouped-row work almost disappears while hot-weight broadcasts still run. This is correct math because the live route mask still selects actual token rows, but it is not useful execution placement. The next safe MORI/AITER helper lever is a bounded replan cadence or an all-rank active-any skip protocol, not a naive persistent cache."
